    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.loader` fails to load modules from runtime paths containing Windows UNC paths. The reason for this is that the normalize function calls `fs.normalize(path, { expand_env = false, _fast = true })`, and the `_fast` argument strips one of the leading backslashes. \n\nIt can be fixed by removing the `_fast` argument.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Add a windows UNC path to the runtime path\n2. Run `vim.loader.find` on a module in that path\n\nObserve that the module is not found\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nUNC paths should work\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-137+g51caf0a3af\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nWindows terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nN/A\n\n### Installation\n\nscoop",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
